  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Kitchen support for IDPs in Shelters in East Ghouta.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since 11 March, 60,000 civilians fled East Ghouta in rural Damascus.

SARC is responsible on their reception at passage corridors, screening their medical status and protection issues including documentation and IDs. In addition to their transportation to shelters and tracking patient information. 

The number of people fleeing East Ghouta is expected to rapidly increase, SARC and the international humanitarian agencies reiterate that mass evacuations of civilians remain a last resort as per IHL and humanitarian principles. Civilians who opt to remain in East Ghouta are also assisted by SARC whenever possible, including access to humanitarian and basic services.  

IDPs are on daily basis transported from passage corridors and hosted at three main collective shelters: Dweir, Herjelleh, Adra and a number of schools were opened to receive them. SARC is responsible on serving IDPs at shelters on 24/7 basis through its volunteers and limited resources. SARC interviewed civilians at shelters including at Dweir collective shelter where they are in dire needs for all types of assistance (food assistance ,medical, PSS, NFIs and protection). Some health conditions (intestinal infections, hepatitis, skin disease&#x2026;) due to long period of lack of access to healthcare. Most children and women suffered from scabies and lice and many are suffering from severe and moderate malnutrition. Herjelleh is another shelter where civilians are now flowing into hundreds on hourly basis, while SARC is offering all assistance to keep their temporary stay in dignity and good service.</narrative>
  </description>
